Methods to avoid deadlock:

1. Always acquire lock in fixed global order
2. Avoid nested locks
3. Use timeout based locks
4. Mininmize critical section
5. Avoid blocking calls inside locks
6. Use concurrent utilities instead of manual locks - ConcurrentHashMap, BlockingQueue, atomic classes (AtomicInteger, AtomicReference, AtomicBoolean)

Ques: Can we create singleton using AtomicReference ?
Ans: yes, but if 5 threads pass this (INSTANCE.get() == null) only one will set. Works but inefficient.

public class Singleton {
    private static final AtomicReference<Singleton> INSTANCE = new AtomicReference<>();

    private Singleton() {}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (INSTANCE.get() == null) {
            INSTANCE.compareAndSet(null, new Singleton());
        }
        return INSTANCE.get();
    }
}

So, initialization on demand.

public class Singleton {
    private Singleton() {}

    private static class Holder {
        static final Singleton INSTANCE = new Singleton();
    }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        return Holder.INSTANCE;
    }
}

Double checked Locking:

private static volatile Singleton instance;

public static Singleton getInstance() {
    if (instance == null) {  // removes thread contention, because otherwise all thread will try to acquire lock object.
        synchronized (Singleton.class) {
            if (instance == null) {
                instance = new Singleton();
            }
        }
    }
    return instance;
}

Correct (safe)
1. Allocate memory
2. Initialize object (run constructor)
3. Assign reference

